nts":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 23343AC86632D66A523070075BF85BEED33AA3E5\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0000\" or less permissive for the \"/etc/gshadow-\" file to prevent unauthorized access.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281070","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281070","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281070","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281070r1165565_rule","rule_id":"SV-281070","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400265","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0644\" or less permissive for the \"/etc/passwd\" file to prevent unauthorized access.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that the mode of the file \"/etc/passwd\" is set to \"0644\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0644 /etc/passwd","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that the \"/etc/passwd\" file has mode \"0644\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/passwd\n644 /etc/passwd\n\nIf a value of \"0644\" or less permissive is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the \"/etc/passwd\" file is writable by a group-owner or the world, the risk of its compromise is increased. The file contains the list of accounts on the system and associated information, and protection of this file is critical for system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"4395","uuid":"c4dfe078-8599-45c7-a10f-a9a9e3b9efc6","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 67B84D5187D3CC7656D2D4103C6CD736C9DC08DC\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0644\" or less permissive for the \"/etc/passwd\" file to prevent unauthorized access.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281071","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281071","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281071","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281071r1165568_rule","rule_id":"SV-281071","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400270","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0644\" or less permissive for \"/etc/passwd-\" file to prevent unauthorized access.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that the mode of the \"/etc/passwd-\" file is set to \"0644\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0644 /etc/passwd-","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that the \"/etc/passwd-\" file has mode \"0644\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/passwd-\n644 /etc/passwd-\n\nIf a value of \"0644\" or less permissive is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"/etc/passwd-\" file is a backup file of \"/etc/passwd\", and as such contains information about the users that are configured on the system. Protection of this file is critical for system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2514","uuid":"584e3d25-c3c6-4921-ad8d-1c428eb0c07e","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 02612EAD43D246516100F4BAB546F10818C9677B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0644\" or less permissive for \"/etc/passwd-\" file to prevent unauthorized access.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281072","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281072","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281072","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281072r1165571_rule","rule_id":"SV-281072","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400275","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0000\" or less permissive for \"/etc/shadow-\" file to prevent unauthorized access.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that the mode of the \"/etc/shadow-\" file is set to \"0000\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0000 /etc/shadow-","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that the \"/etc/shadow-\" file has mode \"0000\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/shadow-\n0 /etc/shadow-\n\nIf a value of \"0\" is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"/etc/shadow-\" file is a backup file of \"/etc/shadow\", and as such contains the list of local system accounts and password hashes. Protection of this file is critical for system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"6387","uuid":"f7eedfdb-fae3-4ff6-b888-3161c44742e1","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4623C7508F1B486690E565F6E8B60617419FE31E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0000\" or less permissive for \"/etc/shadow-\" file to prevent unauthorized access.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281073","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281073","title":"SRG-OS-000138-GPOS-00069","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281073","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000138-GPOS-00069","rule_id_src":"SV-281073r1165574_rule","rule_id":"SV-281073","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400280","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must be configured so that a sticky bit is set on all public directories.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that all world-writable directories have the sticky bit set to prevent unauthorized and unintended information transferred via shared system resources.\n\nSet the sticky bit on all world-writable directories using the following command (replace \"[World-Writable Directory]\" with any directory path missing the sticky bit):\n\n$ chmod a+t [World-Writable Directory]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that all world-writable directories have the sticky bit set with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find / -type d \\( -perm -0002 -a ! -perm -1000 \\) -print 2>/dev/null\ndrwxrwxrwt 7 root root 4096 Jul 26 11:19 /tmp\n\nIf any of the returned directories are world-writable and do not have the sticky bit set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Preventing unauthorized information transfers mitigates the risk of information, including encrypted representations of information, produced by the actions of prior users/roles (or the actions of processes acting on behalf of prior users/roles) from being available to any current users/roles (or current processes) that obtain access to shared system resources (e.g., registers, main memory, hard disks) after those resources have been released back to information systems. The control of information in shared resources is also commonly referred to as object reuse and residual information protection.\n\nThis requirement generally applies to the design of an information technology product, but it can also apply to the configuration of information system components that are, or use, such products. This can be verified by acceptance/validation processes in DOD or other government agencies.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001090"],"reference_identifier":"9847","uuid":"fbfbf385-35f0-44c9-a0d4-66eb083b411f","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DDBCBAF3BA20E23732ACEE3550970A566BEE2530\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must be configured so that a sticky bit is set on all public directories.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281074","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281074","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281074","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281074r1165577_rule","rule_id":"SV-281074","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400285","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must be configured so that all local files and directories have a valid group owner.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that all local files and directories have a valid group owner.\n\nEither remove all files and directories from RHEL 10 that do not have a valid group, or assign a valid group to all files and directories on the system with the \"chgrp\" command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp <group> <file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that all local files and directories have a valid group with the following command:\n\n$ df --local -P | awk {'if (NR!=1) print $6'} | sudo xargs -I '{}' find '{}' -xdev -nogroup\n\nIf any files on the system do not have an assigned group, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Files without a valid group owner may be unintentionally inherited if a group is assigned the same group identifier (GID) as the GID of the files without a valid group owner.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2677","uuid":"e6336e2c-89a8-4dee-baa4-9f263bc1edda","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AE4AC35F9714F78223D3696EC7A73659B26A4B36\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must be configured so that all local files and directories have a valid group owner.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281075","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281075","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281075","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281075r1165580_rule","rule_id":"SV-281075","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400290","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must be configured so that all local files and directories must have a valid owner.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that all local files and directories must have a valid owner.\n\nEither remove all files and directories that do not have a valid user from the system, or assign a valid user to all unowned files and directories on RHEL 10 with the \"chown\" command:\n\n$ sudo chown <user> <file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that all local files and directories have a valid owner with the following command:\n\n$ df --local -P | awk {'if (NR!=1) print $6'} | sudo xargs -I '{}' find '{}' -xdev -nouser\n\nIf any files on the system do not have an assigned owner, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unowned files and directories may be unintentionally inherited if a user is assigned the same user identifier (UID) as the UID of the unowned files.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"6449","uuid":"ded49756-301d-4ebb-be11-f7031c5ab8f2","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 33789564ED82D5EEF0064FC9CAB1C370435F5A5C\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 10 must be configured so that all local files and directories must have a valid owner.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281076","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281076","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281076","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281076r1165583_rule","rule_id":"SV-281076","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400295","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0000\" for \"/etc/shadow\" to prevent unauthorized access.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to enforce mode \"0000\" for \"/etc/shadow\" to prevent unauthorized access.\n\nChange the mode of the file \"/etc/shadow\" to \"0000\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0000 /etc/shadow","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that the \"/etc/shadow\" file has mode \"0000\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/shadow\n0 /etc/shadow\n\nIf a value of \"0\" is not returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"/etc/shadow\" file contains the list of local system accounts and stores password hashes. Protection of this file is critical for system security. Failure to give ownership of this file to \"root\" provides the designated owner with access to sensitive information, which could weaken the system security posture.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2852","uuid":"85937b31-9051-4c21-82af-94fd8e2c74c0","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 813588D84C04A4DF8BF59D6821C20373E2C5B4B2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0000\" for \"/etc/shadow\" to prevent unauthorized access.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281077","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281077","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281077","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-281077r1165586_rule","rule_id":"SV-281077","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400300","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must be configured so that audit tools are owned by \"root\".","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that the audit tools are owned by \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root [audit_tool]\n\nReplace \"[audit_tool]\" with each audit tool not owned by \"root\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 audit tools are owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%U %n\" /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/auditd /sbin/rsyslogd /sbin/augenrules\nroot /sbin/auditctl\nroot /sbin/aureport\nroot /sbin/ausearch\nroot /sbin/auditd\nroot /sbin/rsyslogd\nroot /sbin/augenrules\n\nIf any audit tools do not have an owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nRHEL 10 systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools, and the corresponding rights the user enjoys, to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097, SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098, SRG-OS-000258-GPOS-00099","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493","CCI-001494","CCI-001495"],"reference_identifier":"6085","uuid":"81e36bc8-d674-437c-83c6-f81fca5cbe91","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 861E05C23951EA1471B2CFA69E3A08783154C3F7\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 10 must be configured so that audit tools are owned by \"root\".' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281078","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281078","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281078","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-281078r1165589_rule","rule_id":"SV-281078","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400305","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must be configured so that audit tools are group-owned by \"root\".","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that the audit tools are group-owned by \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [audit_tool]\n\nReplace \"[audit_tool]\" with each audit tool not group-owned by \"root\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 audit tools are group-owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%G %n\" /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/auditd /sbin/rsyslogd /sbin/augenrules\nroot /sbin/auditctl\nroot /sbin/aureport\nroot /sbin/ausearch\nroot /sbin/auditd\nroot /sbin/rsyslogd\nroot /sbin/augenrules\n\nIf any audit tools do not have a group owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data; therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nRHEL 10 systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools, and the corresponding rights the user enjoys, to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097, SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098, SRG-OS-000258-GPOS-00099","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493","CCI-001494","CCI-001495"],"reference_identifier":"3241","uuid":"f21a8245-2f29-46c0-8141-35135e736959","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5153DEC197F7A4FA60317AC480C42E762AC0655B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must be configured so that audit tools are group-owned by \"root\".' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281079","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281079","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281079","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281079r1165592_rule","rule_id":"SV-281079","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400310","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must set the umask value to \"077\" for all local interactive user accounts.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to set the umask value for all local interactive user accounts to \"077\".\n\nRemove the umask statement from all local interactive users' initialization files.\n\nIf the account is for an application, the requirement for a umask less restrictive than \"077\" can be documented with the information system security officer. However, the user agreement for access to the account must specify that the local interactive user must log in to their account first and then switch the user to the application account with the correct option to gain the account's environment variables.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 sets the default umask for all local interactive users to \"077\".\n\nIdentify the locations of all local interactive user home directories by looking at the \"/etc/passwd\" file.\n\nCheck all local interactive user initialization files for interactive users with the following command:\n\nNote: The example is for a system that is configured to create users' home directories in the \"/home\" directory.\n\n$ sudo find /home -maxdepth 2 -type f -name \".[^.]*\" -exec grep -iH -d skip --exclude=.bash_history umask {} \\;\n/home/disauser/.bash_history:grep -i umask /etc/bashrc /etc/csh.cshrc /etc/profile\n/home/disauser/.bash_history:grep -i umask /etc/login.defs\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files are found to have a umask statement that sets a value less restrictive than \"077\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of \"077\" limits new files to mode 600 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"7845","uuid":"bcbd5810-33ba-436e-8b6d-cc251fa56a4f","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4D20B74690FE54E3E6F0C3034570426FDB47A045\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must set the umask value to \"077\" for all local interactive user accounts.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281080","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281080","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281080","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281080r1184687_rule","rule_id":"SV-281080","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400315","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must define default permissions for the bash shell.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to define default permissions for all authenticated users using the bash shell.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"umask\" parameter in the \"/etc/bashrc\" file to \"077\":\n\numask 077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 \"umask\" setting is configured correctly in the \"/etc/bashrc\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"umask\" parameter is set to \"000\" in the \"/etc/bashrc\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n$ sudo grep umask /etc/bashrc\n[ `umask` -eq 0 ] && umask 077\n\nIf the value for the \"umask\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"umask\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"umask\" controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A \"umask\" of \"077\" limits new files to mode \"600\" or less permissive. Although \"umask\" can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". \n\nThis requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"3992","uuid":"a8b0c390-9755-4f18-8208-b25d8777a775","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 348A43F83F7F7A3CA37B3D3F38A4BF7BB5F5EDB3\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 10 must define default permissions for the bash shell.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281081","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281081","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281081","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281081r1184682_rule","rule_id":"SV-281081","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400320","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must define default permissions for the c shell.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to define default permissions for all authenticated users using the c shell.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"umask\" parameter in the \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" file to \"077\":\n\numask 077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 10 \"umask\" setting is configured correctly in the \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"umask\" parameter is set to \"000\" in the \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n$ sudo grep umask /etc/csh.cshrc\numask 077\n\nIf the value for the \"umask\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"umask\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"umask\" controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A \"umask\" of \"077\" limits new files to mode \"600\" or less permissive. Although \"umask\" can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". \n\nThis requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"3888","uuid":"6e3610f2-bf10-4324-a20f-126a22e6c360","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7C157CE324B97B9E9BA775A931740CDD21EBF569\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must define default permissions for the c shell.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281082","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281082","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281082","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281082r1195406_rule","rule_id":"SV-281082","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400325","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can read and modify only their own files.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can read and modify only their own files.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"umask\" parameter in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file to \"077\":\n\numask 077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 defines default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"umask\" parameter is set to \"000\" in \"/etc/login.defs\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n$ sudo grep -i umask /etc/login.defs\numask 077\n\nIf the value for the \"umask\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"umask\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Setting the most restrictive default permissions ensures that when new accounts are created, they do not have unnecessary access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"3815","uuid":"aa464e19-19a4-4316-9101-3c181d90393e","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6597BAA8B44AD0D9D37A492D79823571936C5BFB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can read and modify only their own files.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281083","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281083","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281083","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281083r1184689_rule","rule_id":"SV-281083","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400330","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must define default permissions for the system default profile.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can read and modify only their own files.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"umask\" parameter in the \"/etc/profile\" file to \"077\":\n\numask 077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 10 \"umask\" setting is configured correctly in the \"/etc/profile\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"umask\" parameter is set to \"000\" in the \"/etc/profile\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n$ sudo grep umask /etc/profile\numask 077\n\nIf the value for the \"umask\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"umask\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"umask\" controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A \"umask\" of \"077\" limits new files to mode \"600\" or less permissive. \"Although umask\" can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". \n\nThis requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2536","uuid":"c23f6c60-53d8-4bdc-a9d9-603343ad2981","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 5B5C1C11A862D8829365D98D72A01B087785E786\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must define default permissions for the system default profile.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281084","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281084","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281084","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281084r1165607_rule","rule_id":"SV-281084","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400335","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce that all local initialization files configured by systemd-tmpfiles have mode \"0600\" or less permissive.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to enforce that all local initialization files configured by systemd-tmpfiles have mode \"0600\" or less permissive.\n\nEnsure the following lines are in a \".conf\" file under \"/etc/tmpfiles.d/\":\n \nC /root/.bash_logout   600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.bash_logout\nC /root/.bash_profile  600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.bash_profile\nC /root/.bashrc        600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.bashrc\nC /root/.cshrc         600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.cshrc\nC /root/.tcshrc        600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.tcshrc","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 enforces that all local initialization files configured by systemd-tmpfiles have mode \"0600\" or less permissive.\n\nCheck that all files from \"/usr/share/rootfiles/\" are overridden correctly in RHEL 10:\n \n$ sudo grep /usr/share/rootfiles/ /etc/tmpfiles.d/*.conf\nC /root/.bash_logout   600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.bash_logout\nC /root/.bash_profile  600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.bash_profile\nC /root/.bashrc        600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.bashrc\nC /root/.cshrc         600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.cshrc\nC /root/.tcshrc        600 root root - /usr/share/rootfiles/.tcshrc\n \nIf any files are not configured to \"600\", or if no files are found by grep, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Excessive permissions on local interactive user home directories may allow unauthorized access to user files by other users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"7459","uuid":"4c33f66f-d727-4569-a4c2-d3018714c4ad","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 46E1E24B9D27664D4BE1D5378724F600C25E172F\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce that all local initialization files configured by systemd-tmpfiles have mode \"0600\" or less permissive.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281085","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281085","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281085","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281085r1195409_rule","rule_id":"SV-281085","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400340","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0600\" or less permissive for Secure Shell (SSH) private host key files.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to enforce mode \"0600\" for SSH private host key files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0600 /etc/ssh/ssh_host*key\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 enforces mode \"0600\" for SSH private host key files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /etc/ssh/*_key\n600 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key\n600 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key\n600 /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key\n\nIf any private host key file has a mode more permissive than \"0600\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an unauthorized user obtains the private SSH host key file, the host could be impersonated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"4039","uuid":"718e42aa-b130-4996-b966-398f33b4ab29","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AE867F73B8135399720F5F8A35F97DD488F758CB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce mode \"0600\" or less permissive for Secure Shell (SSH) private host key files.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281086","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281086","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281086","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281086r1165613_rule","rule_id":"SV-281086","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400345","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce \"root\" group ownership of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to enforce group ownership of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file.\n\nChange the group owner of the file \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" to \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root /boot/grub2/grub.cfg","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 enforces group ownership of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%G %n\" /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\nroot /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\n\nIf the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file does not have a group owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"root\" group is a highly privileged group. Furthermore, the group owner of this file should not have any access privileges anyway.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"3542","uuid":"2630a088-f243-4e44-b416-8ff0f18e4d5f","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D8E62F558DFB2AA83E5BFE06DAC630D26686D27C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce \"root\" group ownership of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281087","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281087","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281087","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281087r1165616_rule","rule_id":"SV-281087","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400350","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce \"root\" ownership of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to enforce ownership of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file.\n\nChange the owner of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file to \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root /boot/grub2/grub.cfg","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 enforces ownership of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%U %n\" /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\nroot /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\n\nIf the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file does not have an owner of \"root\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \" /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file stores sensitive system configuration. Protection of this file is critical for system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"6033","uuid":"fbd406fa-010c-44d3-9378-c3e6b6ef3a42","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4503DDFCAD3B3E20732AB7F4F23F7BA430EE1760\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce \"root\" ownership of the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281088","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281088","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281088","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-281088r1165619_rule","rule_id":"SV-281088","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400355","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must prevent device files from being interpreted on file systems that contain user home directories.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to prevent device files from being interpreted on file systems that contain user home directories.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nodev\" option on the \"/home\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that \"/home\" is mounted with the \"nodev\" option with the following command:\n\nNote: If a separate file system has not been created for the user home directories (user home directories are mounted under \"/\"), this is automatically a finding, as the \"nodev\" option cannot be used on the \"/\" system.\n\n$ mount | grep /home\n/dev/mapper/luks-ca2261ed-7b00-4b7b-84cd-8cd6d8fa4b28 on /home type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf the \"/home\" file system is mounted without the \"nodev\" option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe only legitimate location for device files is the \"/dev\" directory located on the root partition, with the exception of chroot jails if implemented.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"8610","uuid":"7d8693a3-fa5b-4d94-8727-bfce08472946","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0684248007F6358829CDE3DD2E26053059EE763B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must prevent device files from being interpreted on file systems that contain user home directories.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281089","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281089","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281089","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-281089r1165622_rule","rule_id":"SV-281089","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400360","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must prevent files with the \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" bit set from being executed on file systems that contain user home directories.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to prevent files with the \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" bit set from being executed on file systems that contain user home directories.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on the \"/home\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that \"/home\" is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option with the following command:\n\nNote: If a separate file system has not been created for the user home directories (user home directories are mounted under \"/\"), this is automatically a finding, as the \"nosuid\" option cannot be used on the \"/\" system.\n\n$ mount | grep /home\n/dev/mapper/luks-ca2261ed-7b00-4b7b-84cd-8cd6d8fa4b28 on /home type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf the \"/home\" file system is mounted without the \"nosuid\" option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"7632","uuid":"7417f739-89f7-4544-a0c6-9832f72a2b50","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 02EEC66F8F5F89C2AC7321CAE90878A9DFA96AC1\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 10 must prevent files with the \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" bit set from being executed on file systems that contain user home directories.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281090","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281090","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281090","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281090r1165625_rule","rule_id":"SV-281090","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400365","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that contain user home directories.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to prevent code from being executed on file systems that contain user home directories.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"noexec\" option on the \"/home\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that \"/home\" is mounted with the \"noexec\" option with the following command:\n\nNote: If a separate file system has not been created for the user home directories (user home directories are mounted under \"/\"), this is automatically a finding, as the \"noexec\" option cannot be used on the \"/\" system.\n\n$ mount | grep /home\n/dev/mapper/luks-ca2261ed-7b00-4b7b-84cd-8cd6d8fa4b28 on /home type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf the \"/home\" file system is mounted without the \"noexec\" option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"4319","uuid":"d4a7d996-7d82-44a4-9078-e6428bf5ac1b","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 79D20BE2AA140E0212F758AD90F0742B0576011C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that contain user home directories.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281091","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281091","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281091","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-281091r1165628_rule","rule_id":"SV-281091","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400400","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"nodev\" option.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"nodev\" option.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nodev\" option on the \"/var/log/audit\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that \"/var/log/audit\" is mounted with the \"nodev\" option:\n\n$ mount | grep /var/log/audit\n/dev/mapper/luks-4e45e1ad-5337-42c4-a19f-ee12ccc1d502 on /var/log/audit type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf the \"/var/log/audit\" file system is mounted without the \"nodev\" option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe only legitimate location for device files is the \"/dev\" directory located on the root partition, with the exception of chroot jails if implemented.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"5376","uuid":"7c4d8768-2ff7-43ae-8a54-3c7ca057fc37","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: AA9C4B11614816137A9DFA7871C5F660B0BD8F1E\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"nodev\" option.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281092","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281092","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281092","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-281092r1165631_rule","rule_id":"SV-281092","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400405","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"noexec\" option.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"noexec\" option.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"noexec\" option on the \"/var/log/audit\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that \"/var/log/audit\" is mounted with the \"noexec\" option:\n\n$ mount | grep /var/log/audit\n/dev/mapper/luks-4e45e1ad-5337-42c4-a19f-ee12ccc1d502 on /var/log/audit type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf the \"/var/log/audit\" file system is mounted without the \"noexec\" option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"5525","uuid":"52771dcf-e4c6-4b1f-80e3-9fd19df4ba24","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CF7E9E5541FFC789475274D078331A6415F5DFB2\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"noexec\" option.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281093","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281093","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281093","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","rule_id_src":"SV-281093r1165634_rule","rule_id":"SV-281093","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400410","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"nosuid\" option.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"nosuid\" option.\n\nModify \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on the \"/var/log/audit\" directory.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that \"/var/log/audit\" is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option:\n\n$ mount | grep /var/log/audit\n/dev/mapper/luks-4e45e1ad-5337-42c4-a19f-ee12ccc1d502 on /var/log/audit type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf the \"/var/log/audit\" file system is mounted without the \"nosuid\" option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"2904","uuid":"fead4e35-2572-42a3-8c2c-bf40478b5902","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2831BF4B63BF31614A2CFF91330D2DB75DC64292\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 10 must mount \"/var/log/audit\" with the \"nosuid\" option.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281094","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281094","title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281094","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097","rule_id_src":"SV-281094r1165637_rule","rule_id":"SV-281094","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400450","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enforce a mode of \"0755\" or less permissive for audit tools.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that the audit tools to have a mode of \"0755\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0755 [audit_tool]\n\nReplace \"[audit_tool]\" with each audit tool that has a mode more permissive than \"0755\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that the audit tools have a mode of \"0755\" or less with the following command:\n\n$ stat -c \"%a %n\" /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/auditd /sbin/rsyslogd /sbin/augenrules\n755 /sbin/auditctl\n755 /sbin/aureport\n755 /sbin/ausearch\n755 /sbin/auditd\n755 /sbin/rsyslogd\n755 /sbin/augenrules\n\nIf any of the audit tool files have a mode more permissive than \"0755\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.\n\nRHEL 10 systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools, and the corresponding rights the user enjoys, to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000256-GPOS-00097, SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098, SRG-OS-000258-GPOS-00099","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493","CCI-001494","CCI-001495"],"reference_identifier":"9428","uuid":"d81e4196-1e90-4bdb-8cef-badfbe9981e2","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: DA0AFC1D99D75D9B1B3EFCA4DC3D53980D11585B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enforce a mode of \"0755\" or less permissive for audit tools.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281095","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281095","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281095","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","rule_id_src":"SV-281095r1184678_rule","rule_id":"SV-281095","rule_version":"RHEL-10-400500","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must prohibit local initialization files from executing world-writable programs.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that local initialization files do not execute world-writable programs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0755 <file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 local initialization files do not execute world-writable programs with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for a system that is configured to create user home directories in the \"/home\" directory.\n\n$ sudo find /home -perm -002 -type f -name \".[^.]*\" -exec ls -ld {} \\;\n\nIf any local initialization files are found to reference world-writable files, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If user startup files execute world-writable programs, especially in unprotected directories, they could be maliciously modified to destroy user files or otherwise compromise the system at the user level. If the system is compromised at the user level, it is easier to elevate privileges to eventually compromise the system at the root and network level.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"3353","uuid":"49ac36f8-d2ac-4eba-9f12-95d20b28936c","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 418BA5B4E1167BA2AE01BAF745A46E5529550EAB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must prohibit local initialization files from executing world-writable programs.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281096","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281096","title":"SRG-OS-000269-GPOS-00103","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281096","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000269-GPOS-00103","rule_id_src":"SV-281096r1165643_rule","rule_id":"SV-281096","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500000","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enable the systemd-journald service.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to enable the systemd-journald service.\n\nTo enable the systemd-journald service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl enable --now systemd-journald","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 enables the systemd-journald service with the following command:\n\n$ systemctl is-active systemd-journald\nactive\n\nIf the systemd-journald service is not active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"In the event of a system failure, RHEL 10 must preserve any information necessary to determine cause of failure and return to operations with least disruption to system processes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001665"],"reference_identifier":"6883","uuid":"e73eac44-3286-4d9c-9c02-770f0c9628af","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 4934C5B40CC5FEFBAA6F4BDF0A3C7A7BF03F6C56\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must enable the systemd-journald service.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281097","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281097","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281097","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","rule_id_src":"SV-281097r1165646_rule","rule_id":"SV-281097","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500005","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must enable auditing of processes that start prior to the audit daemon.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to enable auditing of processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=\"audit=1\"\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/default/grub\" to ensure the configuration survives kernel updates:\n\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"audit=1\"","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured so that GRUB 2 enables auditing of processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following commands:\n\nCheck that the current GRUB 2 configuration enables auditing:\n\n$ sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep args | grep -v 'audit=1'\n\nIf any output is returned, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that auditing is enabled by default to persist in kernel updates:\n\n$ sudo grep audit /etc/default/grub\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"audit=1\"\n\nIf \"audit\" is not set to \"1\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nIf auditing is enabled late in the startup process, the actions of some startup processes may not be audited. Some audit systems also maintain state information available only if auditing is enabled before a given process is created.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"8490","uuid":"34b7dc0a-5d31-4f90-b3dc-f5dc4a68ba74","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: ABF42AF198AF0F9B59D5772263FBF6DF0DA0F56B\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 10 must enable auditing of processes that start prior to the audit daemon.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281098","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281098","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281098","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","rule_id_src":"SV-281098r1165649_rule","rule_id":"SV-281098","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500010","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must audit local events.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to generate audit records for local events by adding or updating the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\":\n\nlocal_events = yes\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that RHEL 10 generates audit records for local events with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep local_events /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlocal_events = yes\n\nIf \"local_events\" is not set to \"yes\", the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, along with the source, location, and outcome, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nIf option \"local_events\" is not set to \"yes\", only events from the network will be aggregated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000169"],"reference_identifier":"5077","uuid":"e074ef19-5f0f-4f1c-8e4d-23c0973dcb11","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: D3495B65B0329FAD3D92BAA9BAB880B41CA20FFA\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must audit local events.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281099","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281099","title":"SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281099","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028","rule_id_src":"SV-281099r1165652_rule","rule_id":"SV-281099","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500015","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must write audit records to disk.","fix_text":"Configure the RHEL 10 audit system to write log files to the disk.\n\nEdit the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file and add or update the \"write_logs\" option to \"yes\":\n\nwrite_logs = yes\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 10 audit system is configured to write logs to the disk with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep write_logs /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nwrite_logs = yes\n\nIf \"write_logs\" does not have a value of \"yes\", the line is commented out, or the line is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Audit data must be synchronously written to disk to ensure log integrity. This setting ensures that all audit event data is written to disk.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000163"],"reference_identifier":"4152","uuid":"2b8ecb3e-3f88-4256-9630-bd42afdaf8b0","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 2A0EE773D5427C2F6B71C73A9B7398F5DE4F0466\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'RHEL 10 must write audit records to disk.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281100","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281100","title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281100","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","rule_id_src":"SV-281100r1165655_rule","rule_id":"SV-281100","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500020","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must log username information when unsuccessful login attempts occur.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to log username information when unsuccessful login attempts occur.\n\nEnable the feature using the following command:\n\n$ sudo authselect enable-feature with-faillock\n\nAdd/modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\naudit","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" is configured to log username information when unsuccessful login attempts occur with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep audit /etc/security/faillock.conf\naudit\n\nIf the \"audit\" option is not set, is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without auditing of these events, it may be harder or impossible to identify what an attacker did after an attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"9999","uuid":"25dc1761-d2fb-4e8a-9331-c5f13c5a1c44","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 43F1CC67300D781216BB0866B220357B6A7B60FC\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must log username information when unsuccessful login attempts occur.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281101","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281101","title":"SRG-OS-000063-GPOS-00032","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281101","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000063-GPOS-00032","rule_id_src":"SV-281101r1195411_rule","rule_id":"SV-281101","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500025","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must allow only the information system security manager (ISSM) (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that the files in directory \"/etc/audit/rules.d/\" and the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file have a mode of \"0640\" with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0600 /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/rules.d/[customrulesfile].rules\n$ sudo chmod 0640 /etc/audit/auditd.conf","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 sets the files in directory \"/etc/audit/rules.d/\" and \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file to have a mode of \"0640\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /etc/audit/rules.d/ /etc/audit/audit.rules /etc/audit/auditd.conf -type f -exec stat -c \"%a %n\" {} \\;\n600 /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\n640 /etc/audit/audit.rules\n640 /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nIf the audit configuration files have a mode more permissive than those shown, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to restrict the roles and individuals that can select which events are audited, unauthorized personnel may be able to prevent the auditing of critical events. Misconfigured audits may degrade the system's performance by overwhelming the audit log. Misconfigured audits may also make it more difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000171"],"reference_identifier":"2092","uuid":"2d20f7ac-1228-49c4-b45e-a35849396361","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A6874FC55AC51482441FE6E190D9E76DE19AE6E9\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 10 must allow only the information system security manager (ISSM) (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281102","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281102","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281102","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-281102r1195414_rule","rule_id":"SV-281102","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500030","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must allocate an \"audit_backlog_limit\" of sufficient size to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to allocate sufficient \"audit_backlog_limit\" to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=audit_backlog_limit=8192\n\nThe setting will be applied on reboot.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 allocates a sufficient \"audit_backlog_limit\" to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon with the following command:\n\n$ grep -oP 'audit_backlog_limit=\\K[0-9]+' /proc/cmdline\n8192\n\nIf the command returns any outputs, and \"audit_backlog_limit\" is less than \"8192\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nIf auditing is enabled late in the startup process, the actions of some startup processes may not be audited. Some audit systems also maintain state information only available if auditing is enabled before a given process is created.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nAllocating an \"audit_backlog_limit\" of sufficient size is critical in maintaining a stable boot process. With an insufficient limit allocated, the system is susceptible to boot failures and crashes.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095, SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-001464","CCI-001849","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"7224","uuid":"d1f98176-cc4a-440e-be4f-714f2509c0ec","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 349D7854585B92E00695340294F76F90BFC9B24E\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 10 must allocate an \"audit_backlog_limit\" of sufficient size to capture processes that start prior to the audit daemon.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281103","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281103","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281103","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","rule_id_src":"SV-281103r1166261_rule","rule_id":"SV-281103","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500035","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must take appropriate action when a critical audit processing failure occurs.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to shut down when auditing failures occur.\n\nAdd the following line to the bottom of the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-f 2","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 10 audit service is configured to panic on a critical error with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep \"\\-f\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n-f 2\n\nIf the value for \"-f\" is not \"2\", and availability is not documented as an overriding concern, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000139"],"reference_identifier":"4647","uuid":"97e27c86-4080-4ed9-9881-8e2515cd10d7","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 132BD9DCC84646A64750D4C17034401A6F15464B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must take appropriate action when a critical audit processing failure occurs.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281104","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281104","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281104","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-281104r1166264_rule","rule_id":"SV-281104","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500040","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to initiate an action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file:\n\nspace_left  = 25%\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 takes action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nspace_left = 25%\n\nIf the value of the \"admin_space_left\" keyword is not set to 25 percent of the storage volume allocated to audit logs, or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator to indicate how the system is taking action if the allocated storage is about to reach capacity. \n\nIf the \"space_left\" value is not configured to the correct value, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If action is not taken when storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization, the auditing system may fail when the storage volume reaches capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"9382","uuid":"590676d0-3f05-4b45-90e4-4f40f61ebcc7","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F777831F1E5B4367FDB3C61ED818574D1B0CA05D\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the audit record storage capacity.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281105","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281105","title":"SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281105","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017","rule_id_src":"SV-281105r1166267_rule","rule_id":"SV-281105","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500045","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must label all off-loaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 so that all off-loaded audit logs are labeled before sending them to the central log server.\n\nEdit the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file and add or update the \"name_format\" option:\n\nname_format = hostname\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 10 audit daemon is configured to label all off-loaded audit logs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep name_format /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nname_format = hostname\n\nIf the \"name_format\" option is not \"hostname\", \"fqd\", or \"numeric\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enriched logging is needed to determine who, what, and when events occur on a system. Without this, determining root cause of an event will be much more difficult.\n\nWhen audit logs are not labeled before they are sent to a central log server, the audit data will not be able to be analyzed and tied back to the correct system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017, SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000132","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"6298","uuid":"9040631c-4fd4-4e08-a068-de357554ea77","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 26210DECED887FD844373BA4CCA433B44294B997\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must label all off-loaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281106","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281106","title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281106","severity":"low","group_title":"SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132","rule_id_src":"SV-281106r1166270_rule","rule_id":"SV-281106","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500100","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week's worth of audit records.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to allocate enough storage capacity for at least one week of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nIf audit records are stored on a partition made specifically for audit records, resize the partition with sufficient space to contain one week of audit records.\n\nIf audit records are not stored on a partition made specifically for audit records, a new partition with sufficient space must be created.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 allocates audit record storage capacity to store at least one week of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nNote: The partition size needed to capture a week of audit records is based on the activity level of the system and the total storage capacity available. Typically 10GB of storage space for audit records should be sufficient.\n\nDetermine which partition the audit records are being written to with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nCheck the size of the partition that audit records are written to with the following command and verify whether it is sufficiently large:\n\n$ df -h /var/log/audit/\nFilesystem                                             Size  Used Avail Use% Mounted on\n/dev/mapper/luks-4e45e1ad-5337-42c4-a19f-ee12ccc1d502   10G  263M  9.7G   3% /var/log/audit\n\nIf the audit record partition is not allocated for sufficient storage capacity, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To ensure RHEL 10 systems have a sufficient storage capacity in which to write the audit logs, RHEL 10 must be able to allocate audit record storage capacity.\n\nThe task of allocating audit record storage capacity is usually performed during initial installation of RHEL 10.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132, SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001849","CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"4648","uuid":"2327caff-5b5f-4f0f-98a6-24264321f45e","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 9E9F76C0480FB046497B5E1906266C4E7612046B\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 10 must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week's worth of audit records.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281107","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281107","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281107","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-281107r1166273_rule","rule_id":"SV-281107","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500105","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to initiate an action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file:\n\nadmin_space_left = 5%\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 takes action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w admin_space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nadmin_space_left = 5%\n\nIf the value of the \"admin_space_left\" keyword is not set to 5 percent of the storage volume allocated to audit logs, or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator to indicate how the system is taking action if the allocated storage is about to reach capacity. \n\nIf the \"space_left\" value is not configured to the correct value, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If action is not taken when storage volume reaches 95 percent utilization, the auditing system may fail when the storage volume reaches capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"1604","uuid":"9b276003-11e8-4616-ae8d-22b03bef501d","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 11551038E429FF9CA15971AE69248C141C20663B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the audit record storage capacity.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281108","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281108","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281108","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-281108r1166276_rule","rule_id":"SV-281108","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500110","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 auditd service to take action if allocated audit record storage volume reaching 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n\nEdit the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" to ensure the system is forced into single user mode if the audit record storage volume is about to reach maximum capacity:\n\nadmin_space_left_action = single\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured to take action if allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep admin_space_left_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nadmin_space_left_action = single\n\nIf the value of the \"admin_space_left_action\" is not set to \"single\", or if the line is commented out, ask the system administrator (SA) to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and information system security officer (ISSO).\n\nIf there is no evidence that real-time alerts are configured on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If action is not taken when storage volume reaches 95 percent utilization, the auditing system may fail when the storage volume reaches capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"5146","uuid":"07d3b3c5-f645-44e2-813c-6d2f61009e1d","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: F1697D29709171FB72E1A042F417E0E0D18F4D85\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 95 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281109","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281109","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281109","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","rule_id_src":"SV-281109r1184691_rule","rule_id":"SV-281109","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500115","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.\n\nEdit the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file and add or update the \"overflow_action\" option:\n\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 10 audit system is configured to take an appropriate action when the internal event queue is full:\n\n$ sudo grep overflow_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nIf the value of the \"overflow_action\" option is not set to \"syslog\", \"single\", or \"halt\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or media.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the audit system is configured to off-load the audit logs to another system or media, and if the overflow action is not set to take appropriate action if the internal event queue becomes full, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The audit system must have an action set up in case the internal event queue becomes full so that no data is lost. Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"8771","uuid":"ceb89d8e-0b0e-470e-a11b-e0e301310f85","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A25300D021639DD5CD07986AF453F125B7A3E3AD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281110","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281110","title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281110","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","rule_id_src":"SV-281110r1166282_rule","rule_id":"SV-281110","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500120","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 audit system to resolve audit information before writing to disk.\n\nEdit the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file and add or update the \"log_format\" option:\n\nlog_format = ENRICHED\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the RHEL 10 audit system is configured to resolve audit information before writing to disk with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep log_format /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_format = ENRICHED\n\nIf the \"log_format\" option is not \"ENRICHED\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, along with the source, location, and outcome, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.\n\nEnriched logging aids in making sense of who, what, and when events occur on a system. Without this, determining root cause of an event will be much more difficult.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001487"],"reference_identifier":"7262","uuid":"c3162983-861f-452c-9da5-7181631c9075","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 86479913E1C6DBA9C72A974D2350E33EB3037E81\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281111","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281111","title":"SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281111","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024","rule_id_src":"SV-281111r1166285_rule","rule_id":"SV-281111","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500125","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must periodically flush audit records to disk to ensure that audit records are not lost.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to flush audit records to disk by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\nfreq = 100\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured to flush audit records to disk after every 100 records with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep freq /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nfreq = 100\n\nIf \"freq\" is not set to a value of \"100\" or greater, the value is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If option \"freq\" is not set to a value that requires audit records to be written to disk after a threshold number is reached, audit records may be lost.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000154"],"reference_identifier":"4462","uuid":"b76362a5-018d-4211-af90-a0210b09cebc","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 0F0D7350EFA63A302EAE56D39A2465E30BA44E9E\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 10 must periodically flush audit records to disk to ensure that audit records are not lost.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281113","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281113","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281113","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","rule_id_src":"SV-281113r1184746_rule","rule_id":"SV-281113","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500205","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume 75 percent utilization.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to initiate an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file.\n\nspace_left_action = email\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 notifies the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w space_left_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nspace_left_action = email\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left_action\" is not set to \"email\", or if the line is commented out, ask the SA to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and ISSO.\n\nIf there is no evidence that real-time alerts are configured on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"8540","uuid":"03610af2-06f8-4a14-a719-538359fe047f","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: E643F2461A78A41E3D8D667C3D522C3FDAAC3DFB\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume 75 percent utilization.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281114","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281114","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281114","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","rule_id_src":"SV-281114r1166294_rule","rule_id":"SV-281114","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500210","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must notify the system administrator (SA) and/or information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) of an audit processing failure.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to notify the SA and/or ISSO (at a minimum) of an audit processing failure.\n\nEdit the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" to ensure administrators are notified via email for those situations:\n\naction_mail_acct = root\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured to notify the SA and/or ISSO (at a minimum) of an audit processing failure with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep action_mail_acct /etc/audit/auditd.conf\naction_mail_acct = root\n\nIf the value of the \"action_mail_acct\" keyword is not set to \"root\" and/or other accounts for security personnel, the \"action_mail_acct\" keyword is missing, or the retuned line is commented out, ask the SA to indicate how they and the ISSO are notified of an audit process failure. \n\nIf there is no evidence of the proper personnel being notified of an audit processing failure, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.\n\nThis requirement applies to each audit data storage repository (i.e., distinct information system component where audit records are stored), the centralized audit storage capacity of organizations (i.e., all audit data storage repositories combined), or both.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022, SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000139","CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"8705","uuid":"ab7e6068-b94b-4e9b-857c-ea274bf9328e","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 3F7CDDC5FC3DB6DFBF562004092BDF826BA5D5AD\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must notify the system administrator (SA) and/or information system security officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) of an audit processing failure.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281115","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281115","title":"SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281115","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013","rule_id_src":"SV-281115r1184650_rule","rule_id":"SV-281115","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500215","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must log Secure Shell (SSH) connection attempts and failures to the server.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to log connection attempts by adding or modifying the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" or in a file in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d\":\n\nLogLevel VERBOSE\n\nRestart the SSH daemon with the following command for the settings to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 logs SSH connection attempts and failures to the server with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*loglevel'\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/90-sshd.conf:LogLevel VERBOSE\n\nIf a value of \"VERBOSE\" is not returned, or the line is commented out or missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"SSH provides several logging levels with varying amounts of verbosity. \"DEBUG\" is specifically not recommended other than strictly for debugging SSH communications because it provides so much data that it is difficult to identify important security information. \"INFO\" or \"VERBOSE\" level is the basic level that only records login activity of SSH users. In many situations, such as incident response, it is important to determine when a particular user was active on a system. The logout record can eliminate users who disconnected, which helps narrow the field.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000067"],"reference_identifier":"2277","uuid":"d567f13a-a5fc-40b7-be7d-926f59e4cb4f","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 7FBF97E277B6D2659C7CB59F4E36CF9A2EB659E3\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must log Secure Shell (SSH) connection attempts and failures to the server.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281116","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281116","title":"SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281116","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126","rule_id_src":"SV-281116r1166300_rule","rule_id":"SV-281116","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500300","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of the \"execve\" system call.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to generate audit records upon successful and unsuccessful attempts to use the \"execve\" system call.\n\nAdd or update the following file system rules to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k execpriv\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured to audit the execution of the \"execve\" system call with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep execve\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -F key=execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -F key=execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -F key=execpriv\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -F key=execpriv\n\nIf the command does not return all lines, or the lines are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Misuse of privileged functions, either intentionally or unintentionally by authorized users, or by unauthorized external entities that have compromised information system accounts, is a serious and ongoing concern and can have significant adverse impacts on organizations. \n\nAuditing the use of privileged functions is one way to detect such misuse and identify the risk from insider threats and the advanced persistent threat.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000326-GPOS-00126, SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127, SRG-OS-000755-GPOS-00220","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002233","CCI-002234","CCI-004188"],"reference_identifier":"6933","uuid":"5feb665e-7d39-4f8c-8127-02f743a91632","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 42CF29CF386C5CA679B19C83AD12C85D6C0A062B\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of the \"execve\" system call.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281117","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281117","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281117","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-281117r1184680_rule","rule_id":"SV-281117","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500310","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to generate audit records upon successful and unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls by adding or updating the following lines to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured to audit the execution of the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep xattr\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls, or if any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary because these affect performance. More rules lead to poorer performance. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"4402","uuid":"ba31beb4-ac1d-45db-b207-c94af4a78a00","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B33D275FA30E53A5B91D5789FD5B092FB66F95BF\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281118","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281118","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281118","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-281118r1166306_rule","rule_id":"SV-281118","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500320","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of \"umount\" system calls.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to generate audit records upon successful and unsuccessful attempts to use the \"umount\" command by adding or updating the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/umount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured to audit the execution of the \"umount\" command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /usr/bin/umount\n-a always,exit -S all -F path=/usr/bin/umount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=privileged-mount\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for \"umount\", or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary because these affect performance. More rules lead to poorer performance. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"6709","uuid":"bce23b57-5d38-46fa-81d5-688404099ca1","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 6562EDDF7E7F373F38A055A029488FF53258B6D0\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of \"umount\" system calls.' matches the expected value on the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281119","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281119","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281119","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-281119r1166309_rule","rule_id":"SV-281119","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500330","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of the \"chacl\" command.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to generate audit records upon successful and unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chacl\" command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nRestart the audit daemon with the following command for the changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify RHEL 10 is configured to audit the execution of the \"chacl\" command with the following command:\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep chacl\n-a always,exit -S all -F path=/usr/bin/chacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=-1 -F key=perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_10_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each system call made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use system call rules only when absolutely necessary because these affect performance. More rules lead to poorer performance. The performance can be helped, however, by combining system calls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130","CCI-000135","CCI-000169","CCI-002884","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"8073","uuid":"c9127db2-b846-42c9-b3ba-aa818d499755","stig_uuid":"a68f390c-b115-428d-9158-12d640fd1211","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-RHEL10_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: EEBAEC15FD0BF770D400D28520D133E9D79DF694\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of the \"chacl\" command.' is not present or not in use on this the RHEL 10 host."},{"group_id_src":"V-281120","group_tree":[{"id":"V-281120","title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-281120","severity":"medium","group_title":"SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015","rule_id_src":"SV-281120r1166312_rule","rule_id":"SV-281120","rule_version":"RHEL-10-500340","rule_title":"RHEL 10 must generate audit records for successful and unsuccessful uses of the \"setfacl\" command.","fix_text":"Configure RHEL 10 to generate audit records upon successful and unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setfacl\" command by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/setfacl -F pe